Fairfield Community High School has been notified of an individual who tested positive for COVID-19. The Wayne County Health Department is working to notify those individuals who are considered close contact. These individuals will be notified with further instructions by the WCHD.

The person is currently recovering at home in isolation. The area is disinfected hourly and daily. We will continue to monitor the situation and notify employees, parents, and students if conditions change.

Thank you,

Jill Fulkerson
Superintendent/Principal
FCHS #225

All other sports who are currently conditioning will continue to do so.

There will be times you may remove it but you must have one to participate. Below I have attached some pictures of ideas for face coverings. We know this may not be a popular mandate, but if we can get on the field we need to make it work. Thanks and keep working hard.

post_text:
Attention Athletes and Parents regarding summer workouts:
Please read!
Due to a potential COVID-19 cross contamination situation with one of our athletes family members, FCHS will temporarily be suspending ALL athletic workouts until Monday the July 13th. We want to make it clear that we have NOT had any of our athletes test positive for COVID-19 or have had symptoms, but we want to error on the side of caution until we have further information on the validity of the situation and to help better preserve our athletes health. Thanks for your understanding and we will pass along further information as we know and as needed.

Attention: FCHS Female Athletes please be checking Google Classroom to accept your invitation to join the StrongHER ACL Camp. Due to the current restrictions, Trainer Sarah and Coach Conrad will be providing this preventative program virtually.
If you have not been invited, please contact Sarah Turner to be added to the class.

Have fun! Keep working hard!

Together we will get through this, stronger than ever!!

post_text:
Spring Athletes,
Today is a day that we all knew would eventually happen, but it still saddens me to report that the IHSA has officially canceled the spring season for this year in all sports. Always remember how proud our community is by the way you have represented us over the years. At a later date we are hoping to be able to have an awards and senior night cookout for all of you who were participating this year to help put some closure on this year. Again, thanks for everything, we love you, we are #mulestrong!!

text: Day #11 Update

post_text:
Day #10 Update

Dear FCHS Students and Parents,

It is essential that we do our part to flatten the curve. We know you are bored and restless and miss your friends. We all share those feelings. But, now is NOT the time to get together and physically hang out with friends. When you do, you put not just yourselves and your families at risk, but the entire community. Use your technology to stay connected! Find creative ways to let your friends know you care!

Parents: your kids look to you for boundaries and as role models for behavior. Help them make good choices about social distancing.

The more we work together and follow the guidelines, the healthier and faster we will get through this.

Sincerely,
Your FCHS Family

post_text:
Congratulations to the Fairfield Community High School varsity scholastic team who closed their season on tonight with a second place finish in the IHSA Regional. FCHS went 2 and 1 on the evening.

FCHS defeated Flora and Wayne City, but fell to Effingham St Anthony in a back and forth match for the championship.
Answering tossups for FCHS were Jason Wright with 19, Lex Gonzalez and Jalysse Kinney each with 5, Karlie Taylor and Xavier Tullis each with 4, Tegan Ruhl and Brenna Freeman each with 3, and Jacob Britt and Phoebe August each with 1. Also participating for FCHS were Emily Burbank and Claire Kakac.

The FCHS scholastic team will be hosting their annual mind bowl in April and will compete in the National Academic Championship in late May.

Congratulations to the FCHS Varsity Scholastic Team on placing third in the Southern Illinois Academic Conference Tournament. FCHS went 2 and 1 on the evening.

In the first round, FCHS defeated Salem, then fell to eventual champion Carbondale. They closed out the evening in the third place match by defeating Herrin.

Answering tossups for FCHS were Jason Wright with 12, Karlie Taylor with 4, Jalysse Kinney with 2, and Lex Gonzalez and Xavier Tullis each with 1. Also participating for FCHS were Phoebe August, Jason Britt, Emily Burbank, Brenna Freeman, Claire Kakac, Abby Marshel, and Tegan Ruhl.

Based on performance during the regular season, Senior Jason Wright was named to the first team SIAC All Conference team, while Seniors Karlie Taylor and Lex Gonzalez and Junior Jalysse Kinney were named to the second team SIAC All Conference team.

The Fairfield Community High School varsity scholastic team went 3 and 1 in a Southern Illinois Academic Conference meet on Thursday.

FCHS defeated Mt Vernon, Marion, and Salem. They only fell to Carbondale by 20 points.

Answering tossups for FCHS were Jason Wright with 18, Jalysse Kinney with 9, Karlie Taylor with 6, and Brenna Freeman, Jacob Britt, Lex Gonzalez, and Xavier Tullis each with 1. Also participating for FCHS were Phoebe August, Emily Burbank, Claire Kakac, Abby Marshel, and Tegan Ruhl.

post_text: 9th Hour Horticulture students started the grow tower project last week! The hydroponic tower is set up in the FCHS cafeteria and will grow Kale, Arugula, Spinach & gourmet lettuce mix this first round. They hope to share their bounty with the FCS Foods & Nutrition classes this spring & further their skills with more diverse crops in the future. This project was funded by a Community Engagement grant from PPG paints.

post_text: Health classes learning about how hard it is to breathe once you become a smoker. They started off by jogging, after 1 minute they tried breathing through a soda straw, then a minute later they tried breathing through a coffee stirrer. At the completion, most students were really surprised at how much harder it was to breathe with a simulated constricted airway. Several even had to stop before the test was completed.
text: Health classes learning about how hard it is to breathe once you become a smoker. They started off by jogging, after 1 minute they tried breathing through a soda straw, then a minute later they tried breathing through a coffee stirrer. At the completion, most students were really surprised at how much harder it was to breathe with a simulated constricted airway. Several even had to stop before the test was completed.
